Author: @jkhdfhkjsdfkhjsdf
Comment: I can. Spoilers. Scroll down for the answer.               At the beginning of the trick, there are only three good apples in the bag. The rotten apple is concealed   in the witch’s sleeve. Obviously, the first two judges take a good apple.  For the third judge, notice that the witch reaches into the bag, not the judge. This is when the witch drops the rotten apple from her sleeve, giving an illusion that the rotten apple was in the bag the whole time.   The witch asks Simon to choose an apple. This decision is also an illusion, for the witch doesn’t specify if Simon is choosing the good apple or the bad apple. Notice that the witch is holding the judge’s arm the entire time. This way, when the witch tells her to take a bite, the only apple the judge can take a bite from is the good apple.  Notice the witch never lets go of her cane. This is because it’s a prosthetic controlled by her real hand. This is why when the “third” hand comes out to squish the rotten apple, the arm holding the cane goes limp.   Hope this explains everything.

Author: @satoruswift1989
Comment: @@rosieposie5852 I have been following them since their ANTIFRAGILE era, so maybe I’m a fearnot. Sakura has been a self-trained singer for the past few years ever since her time as an idol in Japan before Produce 48. Generally, idols in Japan train by themselves to sing because their motive on stage was to make sure fans were satisfied and entertained with the performance, and overall not about skill. However, Korea has higher standards and by the time Sakura was in Korea, she was already 20. She suffered from inferiority complex due to how different the systems are in Korea than Japan. HYBE isn’t known for its vocal training, and they’re quite horrible at that field.   What I think would improve Sakura would be some confidence since in Coachella she never sounded like she was insecure on stage, she was very confident. Maybe a song that would fit her tone, too. I’ve noticed that HYBE has a habit of making their idols sing out of their range (e.g ILLIT)  I don’t even think Eunchae is ready to be an idol, or even, to debut. She lacks the stage presence of an idol and sometimes, you wouldn’t even notice her on stage because of that. Her dancing and singing skills are lacking, but if HYBE was a better company, they would’ve solved that problem. Hopefully the girls would continue to improve.

Author: @carlbaskin
Comment: I have mixed feelings about this, because the audio has definitely been doctored since the original broadcast. When first listening to it, Cynthia was uncharacteristically really pitchy and had timing issues during Defying Gravity, which makes me think there were problems with her in-ear monitor (because she's such an amazing musician and isn't a stranger to performing live). You can still kind of hear the tempo conflicts when Ariana comes in with "if we work in tandem;" it sounds like she's early even though she's actually on-beat. That being said, I love both of them as artists and the performance has been produced really well so it sounds natural and makes it one I listen to on repeat.

Author: @dominican7155
Comment: This drama is a masterpiece, emphasizing what truly matters in life—unconditional love. Unlike other dramas that portray wealth and material success as the key to overcoming hardship, this story reveals a deeper purpose. Watching it, I am inspired to be like Gwan-sik for my family—to love and provide for them so they can rest, even if only for a little while. In death, we finally sleep, but there is beauty in having loved ones worth sacrificing for. That is a life truly worth living.  Spoilers ahead  Together they lived a wonderful life and achieved things people only dream of - had a family, owned a home, a boat, sent their daughter to the best uni in the country, sent her abroad, opened up their own restaurant, provided for their son and grandchildren.
label: positive

Author: @Yuxin-cc7
Comment: I couldn't agree more with you that unconditional love is what really matters in life. The story of three generations of women in this drama emphasizes a mother's unwavering love for her child. In order to prevent Ae-sun from becoming a sea maiden, her mother, Gwang-rye, worked till the end of her life. She wanted Ae-sun to be allowed to follow her ambition of becoming a poet. Despite becoming a housewife, Ae-sun sacrificed everything for her daughter Geum-myeong to be able to attend college and study overseas. In addition to that, Gwan-sik has given his all to the family as a husband and a father. As a husband, he supports his wife unconditionally and gives her love and care. As a father, he supported his family by doing dangerous fishing work and sold his house to give his daughter a better education. Although he worked hard throughout his life and only lived to be 56, his death was tragic for many people since they believed he should have had a comfortable and happy old age. We all sleep long, but having loved ones worth dying for is something that makes life worth living.

Author: @nikhilparmar9795
Comment: It was my fate that I got to witness this story. I had been watching it for a few days, and today the series ended. I never cry, but today I did—because this story teaches us so much about life, love, friendship, and the love of parents in such a short time. I've been away from home for quite a while, but tomorrow I'm going back to be with my mom and dad. I want to see them, talk to them. I cried a lot today, and now I just want to express all this through writing. No matter what you're going through, make sure to watch this series. I feel so empty today, yet it feels so fulfilling inside. I want to say thank you to every character, every team member. I've never seen anything like this before. I forgot it was just a show; I forgot these were characters…  Thank you.  I've seen a lot in life—sorrow and joy—but I have no regrets. I'm 25 years old now, and someday when I'm 50 or 60, sitting with my wife, I'll remember these moments. I just want to live—with happiness or pain, whatever it brings. I want to live my whole life, see all its ups and downs. Even if I can't give my parents happiness through money, I will surely give them love. My father is everything to me—he has worked so hard. I will stay with him. I have no complaints about my parents—only gratitude. I’m happy.  I love you, Mom and Dad. I may never be able to express it openly, but I am yours—I exist because of you. Please forgive all my mistakes, and stay happy.  Maybe I’ve written a bit too much, but if someone is still reading this—thank you. Keep your parents happy. And love your husband or wife with all your heart. Live life fully. Don't hold on to complaints or grudges…  Thank you. – Nikhil 🤍
label: positive

Author: @TV-ji8xj
Comment:
I hope this drama will spark your interest in Korea’s *haenyeo* (female divers) and the unique sound of their breathing, known as *sumbi sori*.  
 Some people have asked, “Are all the grandmothers so rough in the way they speak?” But if you take a closer look at their lives, you’ll understand why.  
 Someone once described *haenyeo* as the strongest mothers in the world.  
 If you also take into account the history of Jeju Island and what’s mentioned above, you’ll enjoy the drama even more. For reference, according to what I heard directly from a haenyeo, sumbi sori may sound beautiful, but to them, it is the sound of life—released after holding their breath for a long time.
